For over a millennium, this practice was done roughly every 60 years by the Cucuteni-Trypillia
culture, possibly to recycle their wattle-and-daub based walls. “Puncturers” made it difficult to combat
these events, despite the efforts of Sextus Julius Frontinus. Marcus Licinius Crassus infamously took part
in these events, then charged a fee to stop them and purchased the affected properties. The Domus Aurea
was built over the ruins caused by one of these events in 64 AD. Houses needed to be frequently rebuilt
after, for the point, what type of disaster that repeatedly swept through the wooden houses of ancient
Rome?=====
fire =====